                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 Nelson, Bert N./86: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-28T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 28, 1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 28—5:55
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>173. [From Perkins.] Legation’s 170, March 26, 4 p.m. The Minister instructs that
                    he has sent the following telegram to the American Consul General at Hankow:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Your March 23, 4 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">3 p.m.?</hi>], and March 25, 9
                            p.m. [<hi rend="italic">3 p.m.?</hi>]. Ministry of Foreign Affairs
                            promises to have urgent telegraphic instructions issued today direct to
                            General Hsia Tou-ying at Macheng ordering him to advance against Red
                            brigands and effect release of Nelson and Tvedt. Please endeavor to
                            ascertain whether such instructions are received by General Hsia and
                            what action is taken by him.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
